File: ANC Deputy Secretary General Jessie Duarte speaks to ANC members during an election campaign walkabout. JOHANNESBURG - Jessie Duarte was born in September 1953 in Johannesburg. Duarte was detained without trial in 1988 during the country's struggle for freedom. She was released and placed under restriction orders until the State of Emergency was lifted. Duarte served in different government and party positions, including as ANC national spokesperson. READ: Jessie Duarte passes away Decades ago, she was a personal assistant to both former President Nelson Mandela and Walter Sisulu. She served as MEC for Safety and Security in Gauteng from 1994 to 1998. She served as SA's Ambassador to Mozambique from 1999 until 2003. Duarte was also the Chief Operations Officer in the Office of the Presidency until she resigned in 2010. Alongside many other things, she was a staunch feminist. In 2014, Duarte lashed out at the ANC when Sylvia Lucas was the only female premier appointed. Despite the party governing eight provinces, she called this 'a political, structural fault line' and 'a strange outcome which is not acceptable.'  ANC Deputy Secretary-General, Jessie Duarte will be laid to rest this afternoon. #DStv403 pic.twitter.com/0DwEUmMye6 